President Joe Biden has announced his intention to nominate Danny Werfel as the Commissioner of the Internal Revenue Service (IRS). Werfel has experience in both the public and private sectors, having served under both Democratic and Republican administrations. He previously served as the Acting Commissioner of the IRS and the Controller of the Office of Management and Budget (OMB) under Presidents Barack Obama and George W. Bush. During his tenure, he provided stability to the IRS, responded to Congressional investigations, and successfully launched the Affordable Care Act technology. Werfel also led efforts to implement the American Recovery and Reinvestment Act and prepare for the budget sequester. He played a key role in the implementation of the Emergency Economic Stabilization Act under the Bush Administration. Werfel has spent the past nine years at Boston Consulting Group, where he helped launch their U.S. public sector practice. He holds multiple degrees and resides in Washington, D.C. with his family.